sentences: Iain Stewart Macmillan (20 October 1938 – 8 May 2006) was the Scottish photographer famous for taking the cover photograph for The Beatles' album Abbey Road in 1969.
He used a photo of Yoko Ono in a book that he published in 1966, and Ono invited him to photograph her exhibit at Indica Gallery.
He attended the High School of Dundee and graduated in 1954.
He moved to London in 1958 to study Photography at the Regent Street Polytechnic.
He returned to Dundee in 1959 to photograph street scenes.
He also photographed "The Book of London" (1966), Yoko appears on page 181 presenting a demonstration of "Handkerchief Piece".
Lennon met Ono at the Indica Gallery on 9 November 1966, and she later introduced him to Macmillan.
In 1969, Lennon invited him to photograph the Abbey Road cover.
On 8 August 1969, around 11:30 am, Macmillan climbed up a stepladder about 10 feet in the air in the middle of Abbey Road and took six pictures of the Beatles crossing the street.
Macmillan worked for Lennon and Ono until 1971, doing such work as:
Kenny Rogers And The First Edition  - cover photograph of Something's Burning, 1970.
After 1971 ==
In the 1970s, Macmillan taught photography part-time at college in Stoke-on-Trent.
In 1980 he took the cover photo for the album Hinge and Bracket at Abbey Road which was a parody of the Beatles photo.
In the 1980s, his work was on exhibit in the US, Britain and Europe.
On 22 July 1993, he photographed Paul McCartney at Abbey Road on the zebra crossing, this time with only an Old English Sheepdog.
On 8 May 2006, at the age of 67, Macmillan died of lung cancer.
The Sculpture of David Wynne, 1949–1967 by T.S.R. Boase (Author), Iain Macmillan (Photographer)
The Beatles After the Breakup 1970–2000 by Keith Badman
The Guardian Eyewitness 1989
The Guardian 2006

sentences: Iain Stewart Macmillan (20 October 1938 – 8 May 2006) was the Scottish photographer famous for taking the cover photograph for The Beatles' album Abbey Road in 1969.
He worked with Lennon and Ono for several years, even staying for a while at their home in New York.
Early years ==
From this work The Sunday Times and the Illustrated London News commissioned him in the early 1960s.
Paul McCartney gave Macmillan a sketch a couple days before the shoot showing where and what the picture should look like.
On 8 August 1969, around 11:30 am, Macmillan climbed up a stepladder about 10 feet in the air in the middle of Abbey Road and took six pictures of the Beatles crossing the street.
The Beatles usually came to the studio around 2–3 pm, so the earlier hour was chosen to avoid fans.
There is now a traffic backup.
Paul is now barefoot.
The wall with the sign was demolished several years later.

The BBC used some of his photos in the series The Rock 'n' Roll Years.
